===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Originally {{zh-l|*𫠤}}, a {{liushu|p|nocap=yes}} depicting a person {{zh-l|*人}} with a headdress similar to {{zh-l|*屮}} and then {{zh-l|*丰}} and {{zh-l|*出}} (but unrelated to these character). Later, the person was stylized to a shape similar to {{zh-l|*夭}} (a man running); {{zh-l|*攴}} was added perhaps to convey the concept of authority, making it a {{liushu|4|nocap=yes}} and transforming it into {{zh-l|*𢾍}}. The man under the headress then become stylized as {{zh-l|*方}} (or {{zh-l|*万}} in some modern scripts). See also {{zh-l|*免}}, {{zh-l|*冒}}, and {{zh-l|*美}}.

As an alternative, according to 季旭昇 Ji Xusheng, it represents a man walking and travelling in the countryside, symbolized by a sprout 屮 on top. See also the original form of {{zh-l|*每}}.

Shuowen Jiezi erroneously interprets it as an {{Han compound|ls=ic|出|放|t1=leave|t2=release|nocap=yes}} due to the later stylization.

